    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1971-03-11T17:08:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1971-03-11T17:08:00-05:00" n="336"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d336">
                <head>336. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Mission to the United
                        Nations</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d336fn1">Source: National Archives, RG 59,
                        Central Files 1970–73, <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> 6 <gloss
                            target="#t_CHIC1">CHICOM</gloss>. Secret. Repeated to Taipei.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>New York</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1971-03-11T22:08:00+00:00">March 11, 1971,
                        2208Z</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>657. Subj: <gloss target="#t_CHIR1">Chirep</gloss>.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_AMB1">Amb</gloss>
                        <persName corresp="#p_LC1">Liu</persName> (<gloss target="#t_GRC1"
                            >GRC</gloss>) paid courtesy call on <gloss target="#t_AMB1">Amb</gloss>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BGHW1">Bush</persName> March 11. <gloss
                            target="#t_AMB1">Amb</gloss>
                        <persName corresp="#p_LC1">Liu</persName>, noting his concern with <persName
                            corresp="#p_TN1">Terence</persName> Smith article (<hi rend="italic">
                            <gloss target="#t_NY1">NY</gloss> Times</hi>, March 10) and <hi
                            rend="italic">Times</hi> editorial (March 11)<note n="2"
                            xml:id="d336fn2">“<gloss target="#t_US1">U.S.</gloss> Said To Plan a
                            Shift on Peking,” <hi rend="italic">The New York Times</hi>, March 10,
                            1971, p. 1; and “China Policy … Negotiation …,” ibid., March 11, 1971,
                            p. 38.</note> said he can’t understand why US wants <gloss
                            target="#t_PRC1">PRC</gloss> in <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> when
                        fundamental policy of Communists has not changed. <gloss target="#t_AMB1"
                            >Amb</gloss>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BGHW1">Bush</persName> said our policy review is not
                        based on naivete, that we hold no brief for Peking vis-à-vis Taiwan, but
                        that we are faced with a new situation in the <gloss target="#t_UN1"
                            >UN</gloss> and must decide on most realistic course of action.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_AMB1">Amb</gloss>
                        <persName corresp="#p_LC1">Liu</persName>, acknowledging the above, said he
                        realized it is because of the adverse tide facing us that we are considering
                        alternative strategies to preserve <gloss target="#t_GRC1">GRC</gloss> place
                        in the <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> but he would like us to keep in
                        mind the following before deciding on any third resolution: <list>
                            <label>A.</label>
                            <item>Pres <persName>Chiang</persName> is engaged in a political
                                struggle and anything which damaged the <gloss target="#t_GRC1"
                                    >GRC</gloss> position in the <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss>
                                would have grave repercussions in Taiwan.</item>
                            <label>B.</label>
                            <item>US should not co-sponsor any third resolution as this would be
                                damaging to whole political struggle of <gloss target="#t_GRC1"
                                    >GRC</gloss> and “pull rug out from under them.”</item>
                            <pb facs="0666" n="629" xml:id="pg_629"/>
                            <label>C.</label>
                            <item>
                                <gloss target="#t_SC1">SC</gloss> seat should not be mentioned in
                                any resolution as retention of seat is of prime importance to <gloss
                                    target="#t_GRC1">GRC</gloss>.</item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>Before leaving, <gloss target="#t_AMB1">Amb</gloss>
                        <persName corresp="#p_LC1">Liu</persName> told <gloss target="#t_AMB1"
                            >Amb</gloss>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BGHW1">Bush</persName> to please ignore press comments
                        coming from Taipei re President’s report as he (<persName corresp="#p_LC1"
                            >Liu</persName>) fully aware of positive points report had made
                        concerning US–<gloss target="#t_GRC1">GRC</gloss> relations.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BGHW1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Bush</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
